            "body": "## PR Checklist\r\nPlease check if your PR fulfills the following requirements:\r\n\r\n- [ ] The commit message follows our guidelines: https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#commit\r\n- [ ] Tests for the changes have been added (for bug fixes / features)\r\n- [x] Docs have been added / updated (for bug fixes / features)\r\n\r\n\r\n## PR Type\r\nWhat kind of change does this PR introduce?\r\n\r\n<!-- Please check the one that applies to this PR using \"x\". -->\r\n\r\n- [ ] Bugfix\r\n- [ ] Feature\r\n- [ ] Code style update (formatting, local variables)\r\n- [ ] Refactoring (no functional changes, no api changes)\r\n- [ ] Build related changes\r\n- [ ] CI related changes\r\n- [x] Documentation content changes\r\n- [ ] angular.io application / infrastructure changes\r\n- [ ] Other... Please describe:\r\n\r\n\r\n## What is the current behavior?\r\n<!-- Please describe the current behavior that you are modifying, or link to a relevant issue. -->\r\nDeprecated APIs and Features (https://angular.io/guide/deprecations) is organized by API and feature area, with the idea that developers should begin as soon as possible to migrate off all of these APIs and features and with the idea that a given developer might not use some area (such as routing). The doc has an introductory index by the version in which something is a candidate for removal. \r\n\r\nIssue Number: N/A\r\n\r\n\r\n## What is the new behavior?\r\nDeprecations are announced by version, so some people (so far, specifically Angular team members) who are more familiar with thinking by version have expressed an interest in a new org for this doc. This PR offers a prototype of a variant of this summary by version. \r\n\r\nNote: Most of those who've asked for org by version are thinking of org by the version in which deprecation was announced (past versions). That order, however, forces readers/developers to \"do the math\" to figure out when they need to move off the API or feature. To help with future-proofing, I've offered the idea of org by future version in which something is a candidate for removal.\r\n\r\nDocs > Release Info > Deprecations\r\n\r\n## Does this PR introduce a breaking change?\r\n\r\n- [ ] Yes\r\n- [ ] No\r\n\r\n\r\n<!-- If this PR contains a breaking change, please describe the impact and migration path for existing applications below. -->\r\n\r\n\r\n## Other information\r\n"
