            "body": "# 🚀 feature request\r\nAllow enabling/disabling scroll restoration on a route level\r\n\r\n### Relevant Package\r\nThis feature request is for @angular/router\r\n\r\n### Description\r\nWe are forced to set scroll restoration behaviour on the app level.\r\n\r\nThere are specific cases, where we actually wish to disable the behaviour.\r\nIn our case the data can change, and the layout is the same. We would like to keep the user's scroll position even though the route has changed.\r\n\r\nRight now we have to drop using the default scrolling system and use our own. It's probably less efficient and won't get updated as much.\r\n\r\n### Possible Solutions Considered\r\nIt could be solved a few different ways.\r\n\r\n**1. Global Blacklist**\r\n\r\n```ts\r\n{ \r\n  anchorScrolling: 'enabled',\r\n  scrollPositionRestoration: 'enabled',\r\n  scrollPositionBlacklist: [{from: /^todo\\/.*$/, to: /^todo\\/.*$/}]\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nBy allowing the `from` and `to`, you can provide a lot more flexibility and a very easy to reason about system at the global level. This is also a relatively straightforward implementation, without needing to introduce any other concepts or dependencies.\r\n\r\nThe downside to this implementation is that it would be very easy to update the route without updating the corresponding blacklist. It's not easy to understand the whole route logic without seeing the route.\r\n\r\n**2. Route Option**\r\nThe ideal long-term solution (IMO) would be two new parameters on the `Route` definition for `scrollPositionRestoration` and `anchorScrolling`\r\n\r\nThe option would look something like.\r\n\r\n```ts\r\n{ path: '/todo/:id', scrollPositionRestoration: { value: 'enabled',  from : /todo\\/.+/  } }\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe positive to this is that it keeps things consistent for the global/local options. It also allows for extension to make it a async function in a future feature.\r\n\r\nThe downside is that it extends the already bloated `Route` options. It lacks the ability to define global cases that are a little more broad, creating repetition.\r\n\r\n## Contributing\r\nThis is something I am willing to try and tackle, if given permission and we can agree on a strategy."
